Steps Taken
•	Connected the dashboard to MongoDB using the existing CRUD Python module from Project One
•	Loaded the Austin Animal Center dataset into a pandas DataFrame and removed the MongoDB _id column
•	Built the dashboard layout including the logo, identifier, radio button filters, and data table
•	Added pagination, sorting, and row/column selection to the data table
•	Wrote the filter callback to query MongoDB based on breed, sex, and age criteria for each rescue type
•	Added the pie chart callback to visualize breed distribution of the filtered data
•	Connected the geolocation map to update based on the selected row in the data table
•	Tested each filter and the reset option, capturing screenshots of each state
Challenges Encountered
The geolocation map initially returned a call back error “Callback error updating map-id.children” if no row was selected. This is because derived_virtual_selected_rows return an empty list, and not None, so if one tried to access this index[0] they would get an IndexError. This was resolved by checking for both None and an empty list, defaulting to the first row when no selection has been made.
